<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="nosql-patterns">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>software-developer</domain>
    <summary>Data modeling for document, key-value, wide-column, and graph stores. Model for access patterns first; choose embedding vs referencing; set TTL on cache keys.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>nosql</tag>
      <tag>mongodb</tag>
      <tag>redis</tag>
      <tag>cassandra</tag>
      <tag>neo4j</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>NoSQL Patterns</title>
    <summary>Data modeling methodology for document (MongoDB), key-value (Redis), wide-column (Cassandra), and graph (Neo4j) stores. Model for access patterns first, not entities; choose embedding vs referencing by read frequency; set TTL on all cache keys; enable schema validation on MongoDB collections. Start with Postgres unless access patterns explicitly justify a NoSQL store.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>NoSQL pathologies (hot partitions, unbounded arrays, missed indexes, orphan fields) only appear at scale and are expensive to fix retroactively. Documenting access patterns before choosing a store prevents premature optimization and prevents locking into a model that doesn't match query needs.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Schema genuinely flexible per record (event payloads, IoT readings, CMS blocks).</item>
        <item>One-document reads of nested aggregates (user with embedded preferences and addresses).</item>
        <item>Time-series workloads where bucket pattern + TTL fit naturally.</item>
        <item>Graph-shaped data (recommendations, social graphs) where traversal beats recursive CTEs.</item>
        <item>High write throughput per partition exceeding RDBMS comfort (>5k writes/sec sustained).</item>
        <item>Polyglot persistence: hot sessions in Redis, cold archival elsewhere, search in OpenSearch.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Strong relational integrity required (financial ledgers, inventory with multi-row invariants).</item>
        <item>Complex ad-hoc queries or OLAP — use Postgres + DuckDB or a data warehouse.</item>
        <item>Team is unfamiliar with the chosen store and project is small — Postgres JSONB covers 80% of use cases.</item>
        <item>Default choice "because microservices" — start with Postgres until pain is measured.</item>
        <item>Reporting/BI is a hard requirement — most BI tools assume SQL.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="mongodb-document-design">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Embed child documents when they are always accessed with the parent and the child set is bounded (1:few); reference when the relationship is 1:many or many:many.</statement>
        <rationale>Embedding avoids joins and keeps reads in one round-trip; unbounded embedded arrays grow the document past the 16MB limit and degrade index performance.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Embedding vs referencing in MongoDB">
        <code lang="javascript"><![CDATA[
// EMBED: user with bounded addresses (always accessed together)
{
  _id: ObjectId("..."),
  name: "John Doe",
  addresses: [
    { type: "home", street: "123 Main St", city: "NYC" },
    { type: "work", street: "456 Office Ave", city: "NYC" }
  ]
}

// REFERENCE: orders reference user (many orders per user)
{
  _id: ObjectId("..."),
  userId: ObjectId("user_id"),
  items: [{ productId: ObjectId("..."), name: "Widget", price: 29.99, qty: 2 }],
  totals: { subtotal: 59.98, tax: 4.80, total: 64.78 }
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use the bucket pattern for time-series data: group N measurements per document with a summary sub-document; set a TTL index for automatic expiration.</statement>
        <rationale>One document per measurement creates millions of tiny documents, degrading index performance. Buckets reduce document count by 100-1000x.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Bucket pattern for time-series">
        <code lang="javascript"><![CDATA[
{
  sensorId: "temp-001",
  date: ISODate("2024-01-15"),
  measurements: [
    { ts: ISODate("2024-01-15T00:00:00Z"), value: 22.5 },
    { ts: ISODate("2024-01-15T00:05:00Z"), value: 22.7 }
    // ~200 measurements per doc
  ],
  summary: { count: 288, min: 21.2, max: 24.8, avg: 22.9 }
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enable $jsonSchema validation on production MongoDB collections; loose schemas rot and allow bad data to accumulate.</statement>
        <rationale>Schema validation catches incompatible documents at write-time before they corrupt downstream queries and reports.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="redis-data-structures">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pick Redis data structures by access pattern: String for simple cache; Hash for object fields; List for queues; Set for membership; Sorted Set for leaderboards/rate-limiting; Stream for event sourcing.</statement>
        <rationale>Using the wrong structure forces workarounds (e.g., serializing JSON into a String when Hash would allow field-level updates) and degrades performance.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Redis data structure patterns">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import redis

r = redis.Redis(host='localhost', port=6379, decode_responses=True)

# String: cache with TTL
r.setex("user:123:profile", 3600, json.dumps(user_data))

# Hash: object with field-level updates
r.hset("user:123", mapping={"name": "John Doe", "login_count": 42})
r.hincrby("user:123", "login_count", 1)

# Sorted Set: leaderboard
r.zadd("leaderboard", {"player1": 1500, "player2": 1200})
top_10 = r.zrevrange("leaderboard", 0, 9, withscores=True)

# List: work queue (blocking pop)
r.lpush("task:queue", json.dumps(task))
task = r.brpop("task:queue", timeout=30)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Set TTL on every cache and session key; never store data in Redis without an expiry or explicit eviction strategy.</statement>
        <rationale>Keys without TTL accumulate until Redis runs out of memory; the server then evicts randomly or stops accepting writes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Prefix all keys with {service}:{entity}:{id} to prevent collisions across services sharing one Redis instance.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents generate raw keys (user:123) that collide across services; namespacing avoids cross-service data corruption.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Redis Streams (XADD/XREADGROUP) instead of Pub/Sub when message durability or consumer groups are required; Pub/Sub is fire-and-forget with no replay.</statement>
        <rationale>Pub/Sub messages are lost if no subscriber is connected; Streams persist messages and support consumer groups with acknowledgement.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="cassandra-partition-design">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Design one table per access pattern in Cassandra; partition key selection determines scalability and cannot be changed without a full table copy.</statement>
        <rationale>Cassandra has no JOINs and no secondary indexes without performance penalty; the partition key must match the primary query pattern exactly.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use (entity_id, time_bucket) as the partition key for time-series data to prevent hot partitions on single-entity keys under high write load.</statement>
        <rationale>A single partition key (sensor_id alone) concentrates all writes to one node; time-bucketing distributes writes across nodes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Cassandra time-series with composite keys">
        <code lang="cql"><![CDATA[
-- Time-series with composite partition key
CREATE TABLE sensor_readings (
    sensor_id text,
    date date,
    timestamp timestamp,
    value double,
    PRIMARY KEY ((sensor_id, date), timestamp)
) WITH CLUSTERING ORDER BY (timestamp DESC);

-- User activity with monthly time buckets
CREATE TABLE user_activity (
    user_id uuid,
    year_month text,
    activity_time timestamp,
    activity_type text,
    PRIMARY KEY ((user_id, year_month), activity_time)
) WITH CLUSTERING ORDER BY (activity_time DESC);
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="neo4j-graph-patterns">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Index every node property used in MATCH predicates; missing indexes cause full graph scans.</statement>
        <rationale>Neo4j traversal is fast, but initial node lookup without an index requires scanning all nodes of a label.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Neo4j recommendation query with proper indexes">
        <code lang="cypher"><![CDATA[
// Recommendation: products purchased by user's friends
MATCH (user:User {id: '123'})-[:FRIEND]->(friend:User)-[:PURCHASED]->(product:Product)
WHERE NOT (user)-[:PURCHASED]->(product)
RETURN DISTINCT product.name, COUNT(friend) AS friend_count
ORDER BY friend_count DESC LIMIT 10

// Shortest path between users (with explicit length bound to avoid expensive traversals)
MATCH path = shortestPath((a:User {id: '123'})-[*..5]-(b:User {id: '456'}))
RETURN [n IN nodes(path) | n.name]
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Choosing MongoDB "because microservices" without documenting access patterns first.</description>
        <reason>Postgres JSONB covers 80% of flexible-schema use cases; premature NoSQL adoption locks into a model that may not match future query needs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Embedding arrays with unbounded growth in MongoDB (e.g., appending every event to a user document).</description>
        <reason>Documents grow past the 16MB limit; large documents degrade working set, increase index size, and slow full-document updates.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Missing indexes on MongoDB fields used in query predicates.</description>
        <reason>Unindexed queries cause collection scans; at scale this degrades from milliseconds to minutes.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Choosing a Cassandra/DynamoDB partition key without modeling the primary access pattern.</description>
        <reason>Partition key is immutable at scale; a wrong choice requires a full table copy to fix, causing downtime.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Storing Redis keys without TTL or eviction policy.</description>
        <reason>Keys accumulate until maxmemory is hit; Redis then either evicts randomly or rejects writes, causing application errors.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent uses raw keys in Redis without namespace prefix (user:123 vs {service}:user:123).</description>
        <reason>Multiple services sharing one Redis instance collide on identical key names, causing cross-service data corruption.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="limitations">
      <p>MongoDB: 16MB doc limit, no transactions across shards in older versions; unbounded arrays kill perf.</p>
      <p>Redis: in-memory only by default; persistence (RDB/AOF) has tradeoffs; cluster has key-slot constraints ({tag} syntax).</p>
      <p>Cassandra: no JOINs, no secondary index without performance penalty; partition key choice is permanent.</p>
      <p>Neo4j: vertical scaling ceiling; community edition has no clustering; Cypher learning curve.</p>
      <p>DynamoDB: hot partition throttling; BatchWriteItem ≤25 items; query patterns must be designed up-front.</p>
      <p>Eventual consistency surprises engineers used to ACID — read-your-writes anomalies under load.</p>
      <p>Schema migration without DDL: hard to reason about, easy to leave orphan fields forever.</p>
      <p>Aggregations across documents are slow vs SQL GROUP BY — push to materialized views or read replicas.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Drive NoSQL design as: (1) agent enumerates access patterns (not entities) from PRD, (2) selects store per pattern (table below), (3) sketches partition/sort key OR document shape OR Redis structure, (4) generates schema doc + index plan + sample queries, (5) human reviews partition key + denormalization choices before code. Treat NoSQL data modeling as architecture work — not an implementation detail. Embed expected query latency targets (p95 &lt; X ms) in the doc.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents:</p>
      <list>
        <item>faion-software-architect-agent — owns store selection + access-pattern matrix.</item>
        <item>faion-api-agent — generates query layer (repositories) once schema is approved.</item>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — implements migrations + indexes under SDD gates.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Document access patterns BEFORE picking a store — the patterns drive the choice, not vice versa.</item>
        <item>Always set TTL on cache/session keys; without TTL Redis becomes append-only memory.</item>
        <item>Mongo: enable $jsonSchema validation in production collections; loose schemas rot.</item>
        <item>Cassandra: model by query, one table per access pattern; storage cost is cheap, latency is not.</item>
        <item>Neo4j: index every property used in MATCH predicates; missing index = full scan.</item>
        <item>Use explain() / EXPLAIN ANALYZE on every new query class; commit explain output to the schema doc.</item>
        <item>Backup strategy per store: mongodump, AOF+RDB, nodetool snapshot, neo4j-admin dump.</item>
        <item>Avoid $where and JS-server-side execution in Mongo — security + perf nightmare.</item>
        <item>Pin driver versions; major-version driver upgrades change wire protocol behaviors silently.</item>
        <item>Test with prod-like data volume — NoSQL pathologies (hot partitions, skew) only appear at scale.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents asked "use NoSQL" default to MongoDB regardless of fit — force them to choose store via the access-pattern matrix.</item>
        <item>LLMs forget partition key immutability in Cassandra/Dynamo and propose schemas that "just need a quick migration" — Dynamo can't change PK without table copy.</item>
        <item>Generated Mongo queries often miss indexes; ensure agent runs db.collection.getIndexes() and proposes new ones explicitly.</item>
        <item>Agents copy ObjectIds across docs without populate/lookup, then "forget" how to fetch the join. Force them to specify embed-vs-ref upfront.</item>
        <item>Schemaless ≠ schema-free: agents drop validation thinking it's flexible, then bad data flows in. Require $jsonSchema from day one.</item>
        <item>Redis: agents use raw keys without namespace prefix → key collisions across services. Enforce {service}:{entity}:{id} convention in prompts.</item>
        <item>LLMs hallucinate Cypher functions (shortestPath() accepts inline path patterns; agents wrap in subqueries unnecessarily). Pin to Neo4j 5.x docs.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint: data model decisions (partition key, embedding boundary, denormalization) — non-reversible at scale, must be human-approved.</item>
        <item>Vector search via NoSQL (Mongo Atlas Vector Search, Redis Vector Sim) is rapidly evolving — agents reference outdated APIs; pin to current minor version docs.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="store-selection-heuristics">
      <p>Quick decision helper (not a substitute for review):</p>
      <list>
        <item>session/cache, TTL &lt; 1h → Redis (in-memory + TTL native)</item>
        <item>rate limiter, sliding window → Redis (sorted sets are O(log N))</item>
        <item>leaderboard / counters → Redis (ZADD/ZINCRBY)</item>
        <item>event stream with consumers → Redis (XADD/XREADGROUP, no broker)</item>
        <item>nested aggregate, 1 doc reads → MongoDB (embed + index on hot fields)</item>
        <item>flexible CMS content → MongoDB (schema evolution, partial validate)</item>
        <item>time series &gt; 1B rows → Cassandra (partition by (entity, day))</item>
        <item>audit log, append-only → Cassandra (write-optimized LSM)</item>
        <item>user + product + recommendation → Neo4j (graph traversal beats joins)</item>
        <item>relational + occasional JSON → Postgres (JSONB is good enough; default)</item>
        <item>unknown access patterns → Postgres (defer NoSQL until pain measured)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="references">
      <see-also>
        <link href="https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/data-modeling/">MongoDB data modeling</link>
